{"title_page": "Mark Courtney (referee)", "text_new": "{{short description|Northern Irish international referee|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{notability|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name            = Mark Courtney\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| full_name       = Mark Courtney\n| birth_date      = {{Birth-date and age|26 April 1972}}\n| birth_place     = [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| years1          = \n| league1         = [[IFA Premiership]]\n| role1           = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 2002\u2013\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA]] listed\n| internationalrole1  = Referee\n}}\n\n'''Mark Courtney''' (born 26 April 1972) is a [[Northern Ireland|Northern Irish]] international [[Referee (association football)|referee]] who refereed at [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?linkID=703&linkType=referee&contextType=bio |title=Profile: Mark Courtney |website=worldreferee.com |access-date=2012-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303203855/http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?linkID=703&linkType=referee&contextType=bio |archive-date=2016-03-03 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{WorldReferee.com}}\n* {{WorldFootball.net referee}}\n* {{Soccerway referee|mark-courtney/44888}}\n* {{Soccerbase referee|1014}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Courtney, Mark}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football referees from Northern Ireland]]\n\n\n{{NorthernIreland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Northern Irish international referee|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{notability|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name            = Mark Courtney\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| full_name       = Mark Courtney\n| birth_date      = {{Birth-date and age|26 April 1972}}\n| birth_place     = [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| years1          = \n| league1         = [[IFA Premiership]]\n| role1           = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 2002\u2013\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA]] listed\n| internationalrole1  = Referee\n}}\n\n'''Mark Courtney''' (born 26 April 1972) is a [[Northern Ireland|Northern Irish]] international [[Referee (association football)|referee]] who refereed at [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?linkID=703&linkType=referee&contextType=bio |title=Profile |access-date=2012-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303203855/http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?linkID=703&linkType=referee&contextType=bio |archive-date=2016-03-03 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{WorldReferee.com}}\n* {{WorldFootball.net referee}}\n* {{Soccerway referee|mark-courtney/44888}}\n* {{Soccerbase referee|1014}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Courtney, Mark}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football referees from Northern Ireland]]\n\n\n{{NorthernIreland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Courtney_(referee)"}
{"title_page": "Benji Joya", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Benji Joya\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = H\u00e9ctor Benjam\u00edn Joya Jim\u00e9nez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|9|22}}\n| birth_place = [[San Jose, California]], United States\n| height = {{height|m=1.73}}\n| position = Midfielder \n| currentclub =\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = 2009\u20132011 \n| youthclubs1 = De Anza Force\n| youthyears2 = 2011\u20132012 \n| youthclubs2 = [[Club Santos Laguna|Santos Laguna]]\n| years1 = 2012\u20132016\n| clubs1 = [[Club Santos Laguna|Santos Laguna]]\n| caps1 = 4\n| goals1 = 0 \n| years2 = 2014\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 12\n| goals2 = 1 \n| years3 = 2015\u20132016\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Club Necaxa|Necaxa]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 2\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2016\n| clubs4 = [[Sporting Kansas City]]\n| caps4 = 7\n| goals4 = 0 \n| years5 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs5 = [[Irapuato F.C.|Irapuato]]\n| caps5 = 0\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2019\u20132020\n| clubs6 = [[Oakland Roots SC|Oakland Roots]]\n| caps6 = 6\n| goals6 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2012\u20132013 \n| nationalteam1 = [[United States men's national under-20 soccer team|United States U20]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 19 \n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| nationalyears2 = 2014\u20132015\n| nationalteam2 = [[United States men's national under-23 soccer team|United States U23]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 4\n| nationalgoals2 = 1\n| pcupdate = March 17, 2020\n| ntupdate = April 23, 2015\n| medaltemplates       =\n{{Medal|Country|{{USA}}}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[CONCACAF U-20 Championship]]|[[2013 CONCACAF U-20 Championship|2013]]}}\n}}\n\n'''H\u00e9ctor Benjam\u00edn \"Benji\" Joya Jim\u00e9nez''' (born September 22, 1993) is an American [[Association football|soccer]] player who currently is under arrest for sending lewd photos to a teen.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Santos Laguna===\nJoya, who grew up in the [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]] of California, played in the USSF Development Academy for De Anza Force. In early 2012, he joined [[Santos Laguna]]'s organization. He began playing during the 2012 Clausura with the club's U-20 team. In September 2012, the midfielder made his first team debut in a [[Liga MX]] match.<ref name=\"Joya, a Promising U.S. Player, Makes a Mark in Mexico\">{{cite web |last1=Sciaretta |first1=Brian |title=Joya, a Promising U.S. Player, Makes a Mark in Mexico |url=https://goal.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/26/joya-a-promising-u-s-player-makes-a-mark-in-mexico/?ref=global |website=The New York Times |accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago Fire===\nJoya was loaned to [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] with an option to buy ahead of the [[2014 Major League Soccer season|2014 MLS season]]. In the 2014 season opener, he made his MLS debut as a 63rd-minute substitute with his side was down 2-0. Seconds after making his way onto the field, a shot deflected by the [[Chivas USA]] keeper landed in front of him. He scored a left-footed shot inside the six yard box to put the Fire on the board, making it 2-1. That was Joya's first MLS touch and only league goal of the season.<ref name=\"Benji Joya RELEASE: Chicago Fire Soccer Club Acquires Midfielder Benji Joya\">{{cite web |title=Benji Joya RELEASE: Chicago Fire Soccer Club Acquires Midfielder Benji Joya |url=https://www.chicago-fire.com/post/2014/02/05/release-chicago-fire-soccer-club-acquires-midfielder-benji-joya |website=Chicago Fire |accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Club Necaxa===\nJoya was loaned to [[Club Necaxa]] of the Ascenso MX for 2015-16.\n\n===Sporting Kansas City===\nJoya signed with [[Sporting Kansas City]] on September 15, 2016, before the MLS roster freeze.<ref name=\"Sporting Kansas City sign former US U-20 midfielder Benji Joya\">{{cite web |last1=Stephenson |first1=Colin |title=Sporting Kansas City sign former US U-20 midfielder Benji Joya |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/09/15/sporting-kansas-city-sign-former-us-u-20-midfielder-benji-joya |website=MLS Soccer |accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Irapuato===\nOn January 10, 2018, Joya signed with Mexican club [[Irapuato F.C.|Irapuato]].<ref>[https://sbisoccer.com/2018/01/u-s-u-23-international-benji-joya-signs-with-irapuato-fc Former U.S. U-23 international Benji Joya signs with Irapuato FC]\u201a sbisoccer.com, 10 January 2018</ref>\n\n===Oakland Roots SC===\nIn April 2019, Joya signed with [[National Independent Soccer Association|NISA]] expansion club [[Oakland Roots SC]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zimmerman |first1=Douglas |title=\u201cI am ready for this.\u201d Former U.S. U-20 captain Benji Joya joins Oakland Roots |url=https://blog.sfgate.com/soccer/2019/04/25/i-am-ready-for-this-former-u-s-u-20-captain-benji-joya-joins-oakland-roots/ |accessdate=30 April 2019 |work=[[SFGate]]}}</ref> He played in six of the team's games during both the Fall and Spring seasons. On April 16, 2020, while the NISA season was on hiatus due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Joya was released from Oakland following an arrest the previous day.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roots |first1=Oakland |title=OFFICIAL STATEMENT: Today, the Oakland Roots were disappointed to learn that midfielder Benji Joya was arrested in San Jose on Wednesday. Therefore, the Club has decided to release him.The Roots will have no further comment on this issue given the ongoing investigation. |url=https://twitter.com/oaklandrootssc/status/1250920135562416128 |website=@oaklandrootssc |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nJoya was a member of the [[United States men's national under-20 soccer team|United States U-20]] squad at the [[2013 FIFA U-20 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/media-library/videos/u20-mnt/2013/u20-world-cup/u-20-world-cup-spotlight--midfielder-benji-joya.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116162548/http://www.ussoccer.com/media-library/videos/u20-mnt/2013/u20-world-cup/u-20-world-cup-spotlight--midfielder-benji-joya.aspx |archivedate=January 16, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MLS|benji-joya}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joya, Benji}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Santos Laguna footballers]]\n[[Category:Chicago Fire FC players]]\n[[Category:Sporting Kansas City players]]\n[[Category:Liga MX players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:National Independent Soccer Association players]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:Soccer players from California]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Mexico]]\n[[Category:United States men's under-20 international soccer players]]\n[[Category:United States men's under-23 international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Irapuato F.C. footballers]]\n[[Category:Club Necaxa footballers]]\n\n\n{{US-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Benji Joya\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = H\u00e9ctor Benjam\u00edn Joya Jim\u00e9nez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|9|22}}\n| birth_place = [[San Jose, California]], United States\n| height = {{height|m=1.73}}\n| position = Midfielder \n| currentclub =\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = 2009\u20132011 \n| youthclubs1 = De Anza Force\n| youthyears2 = 2011\u20132012 \n| youthclubs2 = [[Club Santos Laguna|Santos Laguna]]\n| years1 = 2012\u20132016\n| clubs1 = [[Club Santos Laguna|Santos Laguna]]\n| caps1 = 4\n| goals1 = 0 \n| years2 = 2014\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 12\n| goals2 = 1 \n| years3 = 2015\u20132016\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Club Necaxa|Necaxa]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 2\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2016\n| clubs4 = [[Sporting Kansas City]]\n| caps4 = 7\n| goals4 = 0 \n| years5 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs5 = [[Irapuato F.C.|Irapuato]]\n| caps5 = 0\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2019\u20132020\n| clubs6 = [[Oakland Roots SC|Oakland Roots]]\n| caps6 = 6\n| goals6 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2012\u20132013 \n| nationalteam1 = [[United States men's national under-20 soccer team|United States U20]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 19 \n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| nationalyears2 = 2014\u20132015\n| nationalteam2 = [[United States men's national under-23 soccer team|United States U23]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 4\n| nationalgoals2 = 1\n| pcupdate = March 17, 2020\n| ntupdate = April 23, 2015\n| medaltemplates       =\n{{Medal|Country|{{USA}}}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[CONCACAF U-20 Championship]]|[[2013 CONCACAF U-20 Championship|2013]]}}\n}}\n\n'''H\u00e9ctor Benjam\u00edn \"Benji\" Joya Jim\u00e9nez''' (born September 22, 1993) is an American [[Association football|soccer]] player who currently is without a team.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Santos Laguna===\nJoya, who grew up in the [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]] of California, played in the USSF Development Academy for De Anza Force. In early 2012, he joined [[Santos Laguna]]'s organization. He began playing during the 2012 Clausura with the club's U-20 team. In September 2012, the midfielder made his first team debut in a [[Liga MX]] match.<ref name=\"Joya, a Promising U.S. Player, Makes a Mark in Mexico\">{{cite web |last1=Sciaretta |first1=Brian |title=Joya, a Promising U.S. Player, Makes a Mark in Mexico |url=https://goal.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/26/joya-a-promising-u-s-player-makes-a-mark-in-mexico/?ref=global |website=The New York Times |accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago Fire===\nJoya was loaned to [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] with an option to buy ahead of the [[2014 Major League Soccer season|2014 MLS season]]. In the 2014 season opener, he made his MLS debut as a 63rd-minute substitute with his side was down 2-0. Seconds after making his way onto the field, a shot deflected by the [[Chivas USA]] keeper landed in front of him. He scored a left-footed shot inside the six yard box to put the Fire on the board, making it 2-1. That was Joya's first MLS touch and only league goal of the season.<ref name=\"Benji Joya RELEASE: Chicago Fire Soccer Club Acquires Midfielder Benji Joya\">{{cite web |title=Benji Joya RELEASE: Chicago Fire Soccer Club Acquires Midfielder Benji Joya |url=https://www.chicago-fire.com/post/2014/02/05/release-chicago-fire-soccer-club-acquires-midfielder-benji-joya |website=Chicago Fire |accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Club Necaxa===\nJoya was loaned to [[Club Necaxa]] of the Ascenso MX for 2015-16.\n\n===Sporting Kansas City===\nJoya signed with [[Sporting Kansas City]] on September 15, 2016, before the MLS roster freeze.<ref name=\"Sporting Kansas City sign former US U-20 midfielder Benji Joya\">{{cite web |last1=Stephenson |first1=Colin |title=Sporting Kansas City sign former US U-20 midfielder Benji Joya |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/09/15/sporting-kansas-city-sign-former-us-u-20-midfielder-benji-joya |website=MLS Soccer |accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Irapuato===\nOn January 10, 2018, Joya signed with Mexican club [[Irapuato F.C.|Irapuato]].<ref>[https://sbisoccer.com/2018/01/u-s-u-23-international-benji-joya-signs-with-irapuato-fc Former U.S. U-23 international Benji Joya signs with Irapuato FC]\u201a sbisoccer.com, 10 January 2018</ref>\n\n===Oakland Roots SC===\nIn April 2019, Joya signed with [[National Independent Soccer Association|NISA]] expansion club [[Oakland Roots SC]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zimmerman |first1=Douglas |title=\u201cI am ready for this.\u201d Former U.S. U-20 captain Benji Joya joins Oakland Roots |url=https://blog.sfgate.com/soccer/2019/04/25/i-am-ready-for-this-former-u-s-u-20-captain-benji-joya-joins-oakland-roots/ |accessdate=30 April 2019 |work=[[SFGate]]}}</ref> He played in six of the team's games during both the Fall and Spring seasons. On April 16, 2020, while the NISA season was on hiatus due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Joya was released from Oakland following an arrest the previous day.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roots |first1=Oakland |title=OFFICIAL STATEMENT: Today, the Oakland Roots were disappointed to learn that midfielder Benji Joya was arrested in San Jose on Wednesday. Therefore, the Club has decided to release him.The Roots will have no further comment on this issue given the ongoing investigation. |url=https://twitter.com/oaklandrootssc/status/1250920135562416128 |website=@oaklandrootssc |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nJoya was a member of the [[United States men's national under-20 soccer team|United States U-20]] squad at the [[2013 FIFA U-20 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/media-library/videos/u20-mnt/2013/u20-world-cup/u-20-world-cup-spotlight--midfielder-benji-joya.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116162548/http://www.ussoccer.com/media-library/videos/u20-mnt/2013/u20-world-cup/u-20-world-cup-spotlight--midfielder-benji-joya.aspx |archivedate=January 16, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MLS|benji-joya}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joya, Benji}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Santos Laguna footballers]]\n[[Category:Chicago Fire FC players]]\n[[Category:Sporting Kansas City players]]\n[[Category:Liga MX players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:National Independent Soccer Association players]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:Soccer players from California]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Mexico]]\n[[Category:United States men's under-20 international soccer players]]\n[[Category:United States men's under-23 international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Irapuato F.C. footballers]]\n[[Category:Club Necaxa footballers]]\n\n\n{{US-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2600:1010:b168:9cc1:30fc:9ba4:3886:dd78", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benji_Joya"}
